Simulation Studies for Non-Parametric Sign Test

Bhargob Kakoty, Rajesh Karmakar, Maruf Alam Tarafdar

4/10/2020

1 Objective of our study

The objective of our study is to conduct a simulation study to study various characteristic of the non parametric sign statistic in terms of its simulated size, simulated power, distribution free nature, and limiting distribution of the statistic. The ultimate aim is to validate the theoretical results using simulation. The last part of the study presents a comparative study of the sign test and its the parametric version (which is either \(t\)-test or \(z\)-test).
The simulation study has been conducted in R software (https://www.r-project.org/)which is commonly used for Statistical Computing. The interactive plots explained through the links are made in shiny package of R (https://shiny.rstudio.com/).

2 Methodology of our simulation study

We will draw random sample \(\underline{X}=\left(X_1,X_2, \dots X_n\right)\) of size \(n\) from distribution \(F_0=F(x-\theta)\) where \(F\) is continuous and has median \(0\). Our null hypothesis of interest is \(H_0:\theta =0\) against its three type of alternatives. The three alternatives give rises to left, right and both tailed test. The value of the sign statistic corresponding the selected random sample is given by \(T(\underline{X})=\sum_{i=1}^{n} I(X_i>0)\). Under \(H_0\), it has \(Bin(n, \frac{1}{2})\) distribution. In case the distribution has a non zero median \(m\), we rather compute \(T(\underline{X}-m \mathbf{1_n})\).
The process is replicated \(k\) times. The number of replication in our case is \(k=10000\). This results in \(k\) observations from \(Bin(n, 1-F(-\theta))\).
Now, suppose \(c_{\alpha}\) denote the critical point of the null distribution corresponding to level of significance \(\alpha\). The proportion of \(T\) values exceeding \(c_{\alpha}\) will give the simulated size or power according as \(\theta=0\) or \(\theta \not =0\). Exactly similar methodology is followed when we simulate the size and power of parametric tests for testing location parameter.

3 Simulated size and power of sign statistic

3.1 Simulated size

Suppose we are drawing random samples from \(N(0,1)\) distribution. Let us fix \(n=10\), \(\alpha=0.05\) and alternative hypothesis as right tailed. By applying the above procedure the simulated size is obtained in R. The output is given below:-

## [1] 0.011

which appears to be less than \(0.05\) as we expect. The following table shows the simulated sizes for right, left and both tailed tests corresponding to \(\alpha=0.05\) and different values of \(n\) and \(F\) being \(N(0,1)\).

##   n right.tailed left.tailed   both
##  10       0.0105      0.0113 0.0192
##  20       0.0231      0.0179 0.0417
##  30       0.0495      0.0475 0.0400
##  40       0.0395      0.0412 0.0370
##  50       0.0317      0.0348 0.0361
##  60       0.0465      0.0490 0.0264
##  70       0.0346      0.0319 0.0392

As we can see that the simulated sizes are always less than \(\alpha=0.05\), and sometimes are very close to \(0.05\). The reason for coming most of the values less than \(0.05\) lies in the fact that the critical points of the binomial distribution are sometimes chosen in such a way that the size is not exactly equal to \(\alpha\) but in fact less than \(\alpha\). However, there may be sampling fluctuations which may result in a simulated value greater than \(0.05\). The next two figures are indication of the same situation for \(\alpha=0.01\) and \(\alpha=0.10\), while all other conditions being same as earlier.

As we pointed out, the simulated size is in fact greater than the value of \(\alpha\) for the both tailed test corresponding \(\alpha=0.10\) and \(n=30\). All other values are less than the chosen size.

Next we present some graphical representations of how simulated size behaves as \(n\) increases. The distribution from which samples are drawn is same as earlier (\(N(0,1)\)). The plots are presented for all the three tailed tests corresponding to each value of \(\alpha=0.01, 0.05\) and \(0.10\).

\[ \alpha=0.01\]

\[ \alpha=0.05\]

\[ \alpha=0.10\]

In all the plots we have seen an increasing pattern of the simulated sizes as n increases. For small values of \(n\), the sizes are very much lower than the chosen \(\alpha\). However, they tend closer to \(\alpha\) for large values of \(n\). It can be also seen that sometimes it exceed \(\alpha\).
We can thus say that for large \(n\), the simulated sizes becomes much more stable, in the sense that it is approaches \(\alpha\). This in fact shows that the test is asymptotically size \(\alpha\) test. Because if we consider the right tailed $% $ critical point of \(Bin(n, \frac{1}{2})\) distribution as \(k_n\), then the fact that sizes approach to \(\alpha\) as \(n\) increases can be mathematically represented as \[lim_{n \to \infty}P(T_n>k_n) \to \alpha \qquad \]

where \(T_n\) denote the sign statistic based on \(n\) random observations.

We have considered only a specific distribution to show all the above results. The same thing can be performed when \(F\) is not normal but other continuous distribution. However, as we will show in our later section, it appears that the null distribution of \(T\) does not depend on \(F\). Thus all the things we have done so far will not be affected by the choice of different \(F\). Still, the nature of the simulated sizes and its behavior with \(n\) can be seen from the shiny interactive link which we have shared in the section dealing with power of the test. We just have to choose \(\theta_1=0\), the required \(\alpha\) and the required distribution.

3.2 Simulated Power

In this section we will be dealing with the simulated power of the sign test. Our interest will be mainly of two aspects. Firstly we will study the behavior of power as a function of \(n\), keeping \(\theta_1\) (the value of \(\theta\) under \(H_1\) ) fixed. It will enable us to show its consistency. Secondly we will be treating power as function of \(\theta_1\) (this time \(n\) being fixed) and will see how it behaves as \(\theta_1\) moves away from the value of \(\theta\) under \(H_0\). In our case, irrespective of the distribution \(F\) we have considered, the value of \(\theta\) under \(H_0\) will be always \(0\).

Let us take \(F\) as laplace CDF with location \(0\) and scale \(1\), \(n=20\) ,\(\alpha=0.05\) and \(\theta_1=0.1\). Then the simulated value of power for this \(\theta_1\) when we consider right tailed test is given by:-

## [1] 0.3387

So, the simulated power is greater than the chosen \(\alpha=0.05\). This shows the unbiasedness of the sign test. We will also present this nature graphically. The following table shows the simulated power under the same conditions as stated above but for different values of \(n\):-

##     n Simulated.power
##    10          0.0204
##    20          0.0530
##    40          0.1333
##    80          0.2017
##   200          0.3319
##   300          0.4931
##   600          0.7425
##  1000          0.9123
##  1500          0.9770
##  2000          0.9949

We can see that as \(n\) increases indefinitely, the power tends to \(1\). This shows the consistency of the sign test. Below we present a graphical representation of the same fact:-

The unbiasedness and consistency both can be clearly explained from the above plot. The value of \(n\) for which the simulated power is very close to \(1\) will depend on \(\theta_1\) chosen. It is expected that if \(\theta_1\) is far away from the the null value (here \(0\)), then the convergence will be obtained from moderate values of \(n\). For instance, under the above conditions and \(\theta_1=0.7\) the values of simulated powers for different values of \(n\) are given below:-

As opposed to the earlier case, the convergence to \(1\), in this case, starts appearing from \(n=50\) on wards. Similarly, we can show consistency for different values of \(\theta_1\). In case of right tailed test we have to choose \(\theta_1 > 0\) whereas for left tailed test the simulated power can be computed for \(\theta_1<0\). For a both tailed test \(\theta_1\) can be either less than or greater than \(0\).
For e.g., the simulated power of the test under the same \(F\) as above, \(n=20, \alpha=0.10\) but for a left tailed test and with \(\theta_1=-0.3\) is given by

## [1] 0.3493

which again appears to be greater than \(\alpha=0.10\). Similarly, for a two tailed test and for values of \(\theta_1\) as \(0.45\) and \(-0.26\) the simulated powers are shown respectively:-

## [1] 0.3485
## [1] 0.1555

However, we can choose different \(F\) and different \(\alpha\) and can validate the above the results. 4 Distribution free nature of the sign statistic

4.1 Objectives

-Showing the null distribution of the sign statistic

\[T=\sum_{i=1}^{n}{I(X_{i}>0)}\] is close to \(Bin(n,\frac{1}{2})\) through simulation studies.

-Showing that the sign statistic is exactly distibution free.

-Showing that the sign statistic is asymptotically distribution free.

4.4 Nature of Distribution of Sign Statistic Under Alternative

We know that under alternative hypothesis, the distribution of the sign statistic is no longer \(B(n,\frac{1}{2})\). So now we try to graphicaly understand whether it is really the case. Below we give some histogram after sampling from an absolutely continuous distribution with nonzero median and corresponding graph for \(B(n,\frac{1}{2})\).
We can observe from these following histograms that the null distribution is positively or negatively skewed depending upon whether the median is positive or negative.

5 Asymptotic distribution free nature and limiting distribution

We have already shown that the sign statistic is distribution free. Here we will deal with the limiting distribution of the normalized version of the sign statistic. This limit is achieved irrespective of the choice of \(F\), which we term as asymptotically distribution free nature. The normalized or standardized version of \(T\) is given by :-

\[T'=\frac{T-\frac{n}{2}}{\sqrt{\frac{n}{4}}}=\frac{2T-n}{\sqrt{n}}\]

This converges to a \(N(0,1)\) variate as \(n \to \infty\). Firstly we will consider a density estimate obtained from the sample values of \(T\) and will try to show that it approaches to the standard normal density as the number of observations increase. The density estimate we are going to consider is histogram. Suppose we take \(F\) as weibull distribution with shape and scale parameter \(1.5\) and \(1\) respectively. Then for a sequence of increasing sequence of \(n\), the histograms along with the normal density curve are shown below:-

We are trying to approximate a discrete distribution by a continuous one. So it might not be accurate for small \(n\). However, as \(n\) increases the approximation of the histogram by the normal curve becomes more appropriate. Nevertheless, the symmetry about \(0\) can be easily seen even for smaller values of \(n\). It is beneficial to take \(n\) as large as possible, but for practical purpose we can see that values of \(n\) in the range \(25-30\) works fine as it more or less approximates well and also reduces the problem of taking very large sample. Similarlly we present the histograms when \(F\) is standard cauchy distribution.

So similar results are obtained in this case too. We have made a shiny representation where we can make our choice of \(F\) and \(n\) and it shows the approximation of the histogram by normal curve. The application is accessible through the link :-https://bhargob30.shinyapps.io/bhargob/. For every other distribution we can see the results and it matches our claim that \(T'\) converges to normal variate.

Secondly we consider Q-Q plot to compare sample quantiles with theoretical quantiles of standard normal distribution. Let us fix \(F\) as exponential distribution with rate parameter \(1\). The \(Q-Q\) plots for different values of \(n\) are shown below:-

As distribution of \(T'\) is discrete so it does not have unique quantiles, specifically for lower values of \(n\). Thus it can be seen that in most of the cases same sample quantile is re plotted against different theoretical qunatiles. However, this problem reduces as \(n\) increases and we can observe that the points almost lie around the line \(x=y\). The next plots are for \(U(-3,3)\) CDF.

So we can see that in both the cases the plots yield similar results about convergence of the distribution of \(T'\) as the sample quantiles tend to match with population conterparts for larger values of \(n\) . The presentation shared via the link :- https://bhargob30.shinyapps.io/bhargob3/ shows the \(Q-Q\) plots for all other distributions considered and for values of \(n\) in the range \(1-100\). The conclusions are similar in every case.

Finally we compare the empirical distribution function of \(T'\) with the CDF of standard normal distribution. Let us choose \(F\) as beta distribution of first kind with parameter \(0.8\) and \(0.8\). For different values of \(n\) we present comparison of empirical CDF with the normal CDF.

It can be senn that as \(n\) increases the difference between the empirical CDF and normal CDF reduces. Next we consider a beta distribution with parameter \(5\) and \(2\). The plots are shown below:-

We have created an interactive plot which is presented in the link :- https://bhargob30.shinyapps.io/bhargob4/.

Based on all these observations, we can say that \(T'\) converges to \(N(0,1)\) variate for all choices of \(F\).

5.1 2-Sample KS Test

The testing problem in the 2-Sample KS Test is

\[H_{0}:F_{1} = F_{2} \quad vs \quad H_{1}:F_{1} \neq F_{2}\] where \(F_{1}\) and \(F_{2}\) are absolutely continuous. Here the test statistic is

\[D_{n,m}=\sup\limits_{-\infty \leq x \leq \infty}|\hat{F}_{1,n}(x)-\hat{F}_{2,m}(x)|\] and we reject \(H_{0}\) for large values of \(D_{n,m}\).

Here we construct the sign statistic based on observation from two different distributions and call the two different distributions as \(F_{1}\) and \(F_{2}\) i.e.for example in the Uniform versus Normal Case we take \(F_{1}=\text{distribution function of the sign statistics constructed from the observations from }U[0,1]\) and \(F_{2}=\text{distribution function of the sign statistics constructed from the observations from }N(0,1)\). Clearly both \(F_{1}\) and \(F_{2}\) are not absolutely continuous.Although the assumprtions are not met we perform Kolmogorov-Smirnov two sample test to see whether the distributions are same.

5.2 1-Sample KS Test

The testing problem in the 1-Sample KS Test is

\[H_{0}:F=F_{0} \quad vs \quad H_{1}:F \neq F_{0}\] where \(F\) and \(F_{0}\) are absolutely continuous. With the test statistic

\[D_{n}=\sup\limits_{x\in\mathbb{R}} |\hat{F}_{n}(x)-F_{0}(x)|\]

which rejects \(H_{0}\) for large values of \(D_{n}\).

We now perform one sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test. Here we take the null distribution as \(F_{0}=\text{distribution function of } Bin(n,\frac{1}{2})\) and true distribution \(F=\text{distribution function of sign statistic }S\). Note that here the true as well as the hypothesized distribution under null are not absolutely continuous. But still we perform this test to see what kind of result it gives.

We give the result of sampling from the cauchy distribution with sample size \(n=60,22\) respectively. Clearly in this case it is giving completely absurd results.

## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test

## data:  apply((sign(Tcauchy.simulation(60, 10000, 0)) + 1)/2, 2, sum)
## D = 0.10579, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

## D = 0.16339, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

5.3 Shapiro Wilk Normality Test

We now perform Shapiro-Wilks test for checking normality with the value of the statistic

\[\dfrac{2T-n}{\sqrt{n}}\] In shapiro wilks test

  • Null hypothesis : \(X_{1}, X_{2},\dots,X_{n} \overset{iid}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(\mu,\sigma^{2}),\) for some \(\mu\) and \(\sigma^{2}\).

  • Test statistic :

\[W= {{(\sum_{i=1}^{n} {a_{i}X_{(i)}})^{2}} \over \sum_{i=1}^{n} {(X_{i}-\bar{X})^{2}} }\]

  • where

\[\textbf{a}= {{m^{T}V}\over \sqrt{m^{T}V^{-1}V^{-1}m}}\]

  • where \(m\) and \(V\) are mean vector and variance-covariance matrix of \((Z_{(1)},\dots,Z_{(n)})^{T}\), where \(Z_{1}, Z_{2},\dots,Z_{n} \overset{iid}{\sim} \mathcal{N}(0,1).\)

Below we have given the result for sample sizes \(n=10,50,90,130\) sequentially. Although the p-values are incresing for increaing n, the p-values are too small to show something meaningful, may be this is due to the discrete nature of the sign statistic.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  (2 * apply((sign(Tcauchy.simulation(10, 3000, 0)) + 1)/2, 2,     sum) - 10)/sqrt(10)
## W = 0.96415, p-value < 2.2e-16
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  (2 * apply((sign(Tcauchy.simulation(50, 3000, 0)) + 1)/2, 2,     sum) - 50)/sqrt(50)
## W = 0.99229, p-value = 1.385e-11
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  (2 * apply((sign(Tcauchy.simulation(90, 3000, 0)) + 1)/2, 2,     sum) - 90)/sqrt(90)
## W = 0.99578, p-value = 1.632e-07
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  (2 * apply((sign(Tcauchy.simulation(130, 3000, 0)) + 1)/2, 2,     sum) - 130)/sqrt(130)
## W = 0.99681, p-value = 5.815e-06

6 Parametric test versus Non-parametric test

In this section we will be comparing the sign test with some of its parametric test versions. The sign test is used for testing the location parameter (most of the times median) of an absolutely continuous distribution. We will mainly consider two parametric tests which also test for location viz.one sample \(t\) test and \(z\) test. Depending upon whether the variance of the underlying distribution is known or unknown we can use \(z\) test or \(t\) test. In our case, as we are drawing sample from known distributions, so we have the information about the variance. Thus we can use both the tests.
Our comparison will be mainly based on size and power of the tests. We will be observing under what circumstances the performance of parametric tests is superior to the sign test. It will be also observed that when the underlying assumptions violate exactly opposite things happen.

In the first part of this section we will compare the sizes of the sign test with \(t\) test and \(z\) test. Since both the parametric tests are valid under the conditions that \(X_1, X_2 \dots X_n\) are drawn from normal distribution. So let us take \(F\) as \(N(50,100)\) distribution, \(\alpha=0.05\) and a right tailed test. Firstly we will consider the parametric version as the \(z\) test. Then the following table shows the simulated sizes of both the parametric and non -parametric tests:-

##  10              0.0109          0.0330

##  25              0.0219          0.0429

##  40              0.0411          0.0458
##  45              0.0335          0.0453
##  50              0.0322          0.0454

For \(n=5\), and \(n=30\) the simulated size for \(z\) test is less than that of sign test. However, the simulated sizes of \(z\) test are much more closer to chosen \(\alpha=0.05\). For non parametric tests, sometimes the size becomes close to \(0.05\), but most of the times lies below \(0.04\). It is expected that the sizes become much more closer to \(0.05\) as \(n\) increases. We present the following plot showing the behavior of simulated sizes for both the tests with \(n\).

The sizes for both the tests show an increasing pattern. However, the spread of the points in case of parametric test is less. It shows a steady pattern of approaching to \(0.05\). On the other hand, the sizes of sign test are scattered.

7.2 Bootstrap Confidence Interval

7.2.1 Nonparametric Bootstrap

Bootstrap method is normally used to estimate variance of an estimator. and then using this estimate of the variance we can construct confidence interval for the population parameter.

First we discuss the variance estimation method. Assume the statistic under consideration is \(T_{n}=g(X_{1},X_{2},\dots,X_{n})\). Let \(\hat{F_{n}}\) be the empirical cdf constructed from the observations. we below give the method of estimating the variance of the observations (as discussed by Wasserman in the book All of Nonparametric Statistics)

  1. Draw \(X_{1}^{*},X_{2}^{*},\dots,X_{n}^{*} \sim \hat{F_{n}}\)
  2. Compute \(T_{n}^{*}=g(X_{1}^{*},X_{2}^{*},\dots,X_{n}^{*})\)
  3. Repeat steps 1) and 2), B times to get \(T_{n,1}^{*},T_{n,2}^{*},\dots,T_{n,B}^{*}\)
  4. Let

\[v_{boot}=\frac{1}{B} \sum_{b=1}^{B}{\left(T_{n,b}^{*}-\frac{1}{B}\sum_{r=1}^{B}{T_{n,r}^{*}}\right)^{2}} \]

Now we discuss the construction of Confidence Interval based on the estimated variance using Bootstrap. Normally there are three types of intervals

  • Normal Confidence Interval
  • Percentile Confidence Interval
  • Pivotal Confidence Interval

We are not going to give the details of these methods here. These are discussed in Wassermans book mentioned before.

Now we find the different types of Bootstrap confidence interval for median based on the same sample (from \(\mathcal{N}(0.05,1)\))with sample median as the statistic i.e.\(T_{n}=med (X_{1},\dots,X_{n})\)

Below we give different confidence intervals based on three methods

\[\begin{align} \text{Normal Confidence Interval is of approximate length 0.03066755 }\\ \text{percentile confidence interval is of approximate length 0.02925787 }\\ \text{pivotal confidence interval is of approximate length 0.02925787 } \end{align}\]

Below the intervals are given sequentially.

## [1] 0.03097754 0.06143799
##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.03231661 0.06148001
##      97.5%       2.5% 
## 0.03093552 0.06009892

Now we use sample mean as the estimator i.e.\(T_{n}=\bar{X}\) and apply the same bootstrap method and again find three different confidence intervals.

\[\begin{align} \text{Normal Confidence Interval is of approximate length 0.02335995 }.\\ \text{percentile confidence interval is of approximate length 0.02279723 }.\\ \text{pivotal confidence interval is of length approximately 0.02279723 }. \end{align}\]

Below these intervals are given sequentially

## [1] 0.03737815 0.06050688
##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.03788417 0.06037481
##      97.5%       2.5% 
## 0.03751022 0.06000086

From the above results in sampling from normal distribution we summarize-

  1. \(95\%\) CI based on sign statistic \(S\) is of approximate length \(0.02911278\).
  2. \(95\%\) CI based on \(med(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})\) using bootstrap is of approximate length \(0.02925787\).
  3. \(95\%\) CI based on \(\bar{X}\) using bootstrap is of approximate length \(0.02279723\).

So in case of (2), the interval is more or less of the same length as in (1) with the added advantage compared to (1) is that it is much more symmetric around 0.05.

But when we use mean in (3) as the statistic, then the confidence interval is much more shorter compared to both (1) and (2). So if we graphically find that there is a high possibility that our distribution has mean and median approximately same and not heavy-tailed, it is much better to apply bootstrap with sample mean than using sign statistic. But we know sample median is much more robust than sample mean. So if we sample from heavy-tailed distribution, we can use bootstrap with median.

Now we sample from a heavy tailed distribution compared to \(\mathcal{N}(0.05,1)\), say \(\mathcal{C}(0.05,1)\) (\(Cauchy\) distribution with location \(0.05\) and scale \(1\)). And observe the same kind of Bootstrap confidence intervals as before to see the differences between bootstrap with \(mean\) and \(median\) as the statistic. Note that \(Cauchy\) distribution does not have finite mean.

At first e use sample median as the statistic i.e.\(T_{n}=med (X_{1},\dots,X_{n})\).

Below we give different confidence intervals based on three methods

\[\begin{align} \text{Normal Confidence Interval is of approximate length 0.03885811 }\\ \text{percentile confidence interval is of approximate length 0.03838861 }\\ \text{pivotal confidence interval is of approximate length 0.03838861 } \end{align}\]

Below the intervals are given sequentially.

## [1] 0.04277211 0.08163022
##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.04339672 0.08178533
##      97.5%       2.5% 
## 0.04261700 0.08100561

Now we use sample mean as the estimator i.e.\(T_{n}=\bar{X}\) and apply the same bootstrap method and again find three different confidence intervals.

\[\begin{align} \text{Normal Confidence Interval is of approximate length 3.854458 }.\\ \text{percentile confidence interval is of approximate length 4.018421 }.\\ \text{pivotal confidence interval is of length approximately 4.018421 }. \end{align}\]

Below these intervals are given sequentially

## [1] -1.779393  2.179277
##      2.5%     97.5% 
## -1.893965  2.124456
##     97.5%      2.5% 
## -1.724572  2.293849

From the above results in sampling from Cauchy distribution we summarize-

  1. \(95\%\) CI based on sign statistic \(S\) is of approximate length \(0.03813889\).
  2. \(95\%\) CI based on \(med(X_{1},\dots,X_{n})\) using bootstrap is of approximate length \(0.03838861\).
  3. \(95\%\) CI based on \(\bar{X}\) using bootstrap is of approximate length \(3.854458\).

So observe that confidence interval based on sign statistic is the superior one. Observe that confidence interval based on sample mean is performing very poorly. This is due to the fact that sample mean is heavily non-robust for population mean (although in this case population mean does not exist) when we sample from a heavy-tailed distribution.

So in this case it is better to proceed with Sign-test to find confidence interval.

7.2.2 Parametric Bootstrap

All the above methods are non-parametric. Here we perform a parametric version of bootstrap. In this method we first estimate the median (in this case same as mean) by sample mean (if we sample from heavy-tailed distribution, it will be better to use sample median) and then sample from the new theoretical distribution with estimated parameter.

First we perform for sample from \(\mathcal{N}(0.05,1)\)-

Here the\(95\%\) CI is of length close to \(0.02255331\).

##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.03901396 0.06184149

Clearly the interval based on sample mean using parametric bootstrap performs the best among all the methods earlier.

If we use median then the length becomes close to \(0.02920211\), which is very close to its nonparametric version.

##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.03614608 0.06530947

Now we find the interval for sample from \(\mathcal{C}(0.05,1)\)-

Here we use the estimator of population median as sample median (which is quite a good estimator for Cauchy distribution).

Here the \(95\%\) CI is of length close to \(0.0291904\), which competes very well with confidence interval based on sign statistic.

##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.04451778 0.07368117

We graphically show the confidence intervals

So from our simulation study we observe that it is much better to apply parametric bootstrap than Sign Statistic approach to construct confidence interval for the location parameter.But one big lesson we have learned from the simulation studies is that we should investigate the nature of distribution (from which the sample is coming) very carefully to decide which estimator for population parameter we should use for parametric bootstrap.
